meta.executive_summary: System status: 5 healthy, 3 tripwire, 0 stress. Biggest moves: Initial Jobless Claims is down 6.3% YoY. Revolving Consumer Credit is down 2.5% YoY. Job Openings is up 0.7% YoY.

metrics.title: Card 30+ Delinquency
metrics.subtitle: FRED: DRCCLACBS (%; quarterly)
metrics.definition: Share of credit-card balances at least 30 days past due (all banks).
metrics.why: Rising delinquency is an early sign of household strain.

metrics.title: Net Charge-off Rate
metrics.subtitle: FRED: CORCCACBS (%; quarterly)
metrics.definition: Portion of credit-card loans written off as uncollectible (all banks).
metrics.why: Charge-offs typically lag delinquencies but confirm credit deterioration.

metrics.title: Debt Service Burden
metrics.subtitle: FRED: TDSP (%; quarterly)
metrics.definition: Household debt payments as a percent of disposable personal income.
metrics.why: Higher debt service leaves less buffer to absorb shocks.

metrics.title: Mortgage 30+ Delinquency
metrics.subtitle: FRED: DRSFRMACBS (%; quarterly)
metrics.definition: Share of residential mortgages 30+ days delinquent (all commercial banks).
metrics.why: Mortgage delinquencies can jump in downturns and housing stress episodes.

metrics.title: Revolving Consumer Credit
metrics.subtitle: FRED: REVOLSL ($B; monthly)
metrics.definition: Total revolving consumer credit outstanding (primarily credit cards).
metrics.why: Rapid growth can signal households leaning on credit.

metrics.title: Job Openings
metrics.subtitle: FRED: JTSJOL (millions; monthly)
metrics.definition: Job openings (JOLTS). Proxy for labor demand.
metrics.why: Falling openings often precede labor market cooling.

metrics.title: Unemployment Rate
metrics.subtitle: FRED: UNRATE (%; monthly)
metrics.why: Rising unemployment tends to worsen credit performance.

metrics.title: Initial Jobless Claims
metrics.subtitle: FRED: ICSA (thousands; weekly)
metrics.definition: Weekly initial claims for unemployment insurance.
metrics.why: Claims are a fast-turn labor stress signal; spikes can precede higher unemployment.
